This game has been updated and received some fixes for controller support! But it isn't there just yet, as there is room for improvement. Here are the downs of such implemented controller support: #1 The game will now move on after the initial screen after Unity detects a HID controller is connected to the phone and working; [OK] #2 Character customization screen, menus, conversation dialog options are touch screen only; [NEEDS FIX] #3 During a conversation, I can pass the dialogs with the A button, but I can't select a conversation dialog with the same button. I have to use touch control. Why is that? [NEEDS FIX] #4 I get close to an NPC, press X and it triggers conversation mode; Once the conversation is over, why can't I get out of it using a physical controller button, such as B? I have to use the 'Bye' touch control. Ugh! [NEEDS FIX] #5 Touch controls aren't supposed to be "printed" on screen after Unity detects an HID Bluetooth controller - I suggest using the custom buttons menu and give us an option to NOT display touch controls. Furthermore please update the game input tutorial to mention physical controller buttons, not touch controls, after Unity detects a controller is working during gameplay; [NEEDS FIX] #6 The backpack is accessible with start button, but once in there, there is no way to move to the next tab, which is a pain, especially when I need to check the map every so often. Switching tabs in the backpack should be done with shoulder buttons (L1 or R1) [NEEDS FIX] #7 There is no way to access or edit the four quick access slots using a physical controller. [NEEDS FIX] Guys, HID controller support for this game is here, it just needs some fixes. We can do this! I used a Saitake STF-7000 controller (HID mode) with XBOX buttons layout FYI.

I quit the game while it was frozen, and next time I opened my save file my player was met with the absolute void, and he of course died a few seconds later. I restarted from my last save, only to realize the VOID was my last save. I had been playing for 3 hours. At least you could make it be able to load the save before the last one . I think its quite an adequate action RPG for mobile phone. It's not Diablo 
2 or Skyrim on desktop. Its much more simplified, but fun and challenging. 
Many quests, large enough levels for some exploring, and the ability to 
upgrade your character and weapons which is always a satisfying and 
essential element of an action RPG. The combat controls can be infuriating 
at times; press the hack button and he don't hack! Just stands there 
getting blasted by enemies, wish that was better. It's also extremely 
glitchy, one minute the poison water is there then it isn't. Not a polished 
game, but as a mobile experience on my 3" screen? It's worth it!

Fable/Skyrim style, extremely well made (few minor glitches concerning home decor and some mountains, if there's any others you should just try moving that 486 MB monster to your SD card or/and getting a good phone while cancelling background processes and maybe even auto-updates, those are actually on your end pplz, and the fact some surfaces in the cliffs aren't entirely solid isn't a glitch-it saved space and download data for us who actually have to buy data), too bad you can't place stuff on the shelf or hang the pictures up.  And you're a bad man for making the couch face only one way, moving it can be impossible. I like how you can crank it up to hard and down to easy at any time, it'd be better if you can crank it up to hard and kill everyone in Aven,  but I'm glad it works and fits on a phone.  Played it for 30 minutes before I figured out I wasn't supposed to be born in the 21st century, but I beat it in less than two days mostly on Hardest and Auto-Aim Off (but that's just because I wanted all the good stuff, I could've beaten it in a day and a half if I didn't actually play around).  Truly you've nearly outdone yourself when it's man vs. dinosaur and I really like it and all, but out of all the concepts and schemes out there, did it have to be Orcs and Elves (again) as the myth... So great job, By the way what is it going to take for me to get the Ancient Realm.  But if you added all those suggestions youd have a game you can either charge more for or a better game, but theres no ancient realm on mine, I wanted to find a blood-black ruby and go against nightmare creatures, and the special swords had no function.  Great game tho, I only play first and third person rpgs, not just third or side scrolls.

Controls are some of the best ive seen yet in this type of game on android. the scheme really works, you adapt to it after a few enemy encounters. just make sure to change the sensitivity in the options, Touch controls are never gonna be a 5 anyway. Overall very pleased with it.

Simply amazing. This game is spectacular. A true RPG experience. A large, exploration heavy open world, complex leveling system, and really entertaining and engaging combat make this game stand out above all others. An above par UI, amazing looking graphics, and overall just a REALLY GREAT rpg expierence. I couldn't say enough about this game. But casual players be warned, this game is NOT EASY, and its far from a hack and slash game. You will have to grind in the lower levels otherwise you will get slaughtered by harder enemies. And you have to think during combat, parry with shield, roll out of combat to escape death etc, and save often.  This game is as close to a TES expierence on mobile you will get. Amazing game.

Had some money sitting on my account so thought I'd try this.     The graphics aren't as good as the pictures. The hair looks ridiculous and shiny like plastic. The texture on the certain faces have hair with them that look okay, but the added hair selections just look ridiculous.     The controls are not as simple as they should be. To look around you have to keep swiping the screen. Most games have your screen continue to rotate as your finger stays swiped from where you initially touch the screen.     Most detrimental bug: The game freezes on load screens. You have to close out and reopen to continue playing. Sometimes after doing this your save will have you instantly falling beneath the map to your death in about 3 seconds. To fix, pause immediately, and fast travel somewhere.    Other bugs: Options like sensitivity and view distance don't seem to do anything.  Edit: 1 star because im 64 mins in and my save won't load.

Ravensword: Shadowlands is an impressive and engaging mobile RPG. The combat and gameplay is smooth and fun, and the world is very immersive. I was very surprised at the notable amount of items, mounts, and NPCs this game has to offer. While the plot wasn't exactly original and it isn't easy to get tied up into the story, the gameplay far made up for this flaw. I did wish for a bit more character development, as the diversity of the NPCs was quite limited. I also wish you could play as a female. However, despite it's rather small flaws, Ravensword: Shadowlands is a fantastic game, and if you're any fan of adventure games, this game is worth the purchase!

I want to start off this review by asking this: what the blue f*** were you thinking? You state on the main page that this game is Moga pro controller compatible, but judging by the last hour of f****** around with this game I can honestly say you must have tested that theory with emaciated gerbils. mode a didn't actually do anything. upon startup it just asked me if I wanted to use the controller, but it had no intention of following through with my answer. mode B actually went a step further. It refused to let my game even start, with a nice frozen screen upon startup. I guess it would be one thing to live with this, but then there are other small things. For instance, where the hell did you get those screenshots? A great deal of work has gone into this game. It’s a beautiful stunning game that reminds me of Oblivion.  Would have given 5 stars but there are a few things which need addressing. 1: Real shame there's only about 16 or so very short side quests and there are no decision based, multi-part quests at all. The only decision part is accepting the quest or not. 2: Quest marker is a bit buggy and hard to find/follow sometimes. 3: Not enough chests, and could do with respawning random contents for longer playability. 4: You can buy houses but there is no real way to store your stuff (you can’t buy a chest etc). 5: There’s no gems later in the game to enhance your stuff as you have already used what gems there are earlier in the game. 6: As well as the small map of Avan it would help if you had a choice of a bigger map.  7: Does crash rather a lot after the loading screen going from one area to another. These are only small issues believe or not, I absolutely love this game and I would highly recommend this game to anybody who likes RPG/Action/FPS games.

I initially wrote a long review but i guess google couldn't fit it all in 1 paragraph, so here is the short version: Sound 4/5: Almost as good as Skyrim, but not quite there yet. Graphics: 2/5: Buggy and unclear. Mount&blade from 2008 has better graphics. Gameplay: 3/5: Repetitive, archery is overpowered, magic is non-existent. Lore: 2/5: Lacks logic, too little side-quests, main quest-line is too cliche RPG. AI: 1/5: NPCs wander around, monsters don't do anything even if you attack their friends. In conclusion: A decent time-killer, but spend your 7 bucks on a steam sale.

The presentation is awesome, love the music, enviroments and enemies. Character development is ok but could be better, you do feel pretty weak in the beggining and badass towards the end. There are pretty much only two options how to develop your character and that is ranged (bows and crossbows - put points into agility) and melee (swords, axes, blunt - put points into strenght), magic is not an option since, except a few runestones useful only to complete the main storyline, there is NO MAGIC AT ALL. Some skills, features and many items are only there to be there and have no use whatsoever. Also, for an rpg the game is quite short (about 7 hours to complete the main storyline and most of the side quests - which are really simple and uninteresting). Gameworld is pretty big (for mobile platforms) but lacks content (1-2 caves in each area and thats it...). The advertised decision based quests is just a lie since the very few decisions there are have literally no effect on the outcome, the gameplay or the gameworld whatsoever. I give it 4/5 mostly because as far as i know its a first attempt for a game like this on mobile and it gives hope for the future.

*Review based on my experience up until obtaining the first Ravenstone.*  Overall this game is too simple. There is a serious lack of NPCs, and most houses either cannot be entered, or have nothing of interest inside. The world isn't as open as we are lead to believe. The main town of Aven sits in the middle of the world, and whichever of the four exits you choose (North, South, East, or West) you can only continue in that direction. On top of that, there are typically only 3 locations in any direction, and only one is an actual dungeon, and a pretty small dungeon at that. As for combat, playing with sword and shield is reminiscent of past Elder Scrolls games, except for the lack of various power attacks, and shield bashing. Archery is completely unfair, as most enemies are melee only, so you can simply walk backwards and stay out of their reach. Also, I really wish there were boss battles, in the main quest dungeons, and maybe even some puzzles. Clearing a dungeons is very unfulfilling in this game.  This studio has potential, and I hope the next installment is leaps and bounds over this one.

Don't do what I did.  I ignored the other reviews that said that MOGA controllers don't work, and bought this game anyway.  I figured, hey Crescent Moon intentionally put "Now supports MOGA Pro controllers (Mode A)" in their description, so it must be true.  Well, it wasn't.  The other reviewers were right, MOGA controllers do not work, and neither did my basic HID controller.  I bought this game because it looked awesome, and immediately after that I bought the MOGA Pro Power controller to use with this game.  Let me be clear, the whole reason why I bought the MOGA controller was because this game said that it supported it.  It was a lie, and now I am out a lot of money.  Thanks a lot.  This is the last Crescent Moon app that I am going to buy.  For your reference, I am running on an LG G2 with Android 4.4.2 installed.

Without a doubt the best Android game I've played. I have been messing around with free games on my Galaxy S4 and haven't felt like anything has been pushing the device to its full potential. This game blew me away. Stunning graphics, beautiful world, amazing detail. I recommend it for fans of the Elder Scroll series. I'm not saying it's on Skyrim's level. But as close as you'll get on a hand held device. Have been playing for an hour now with no issues. EDIT: The longer you play the more the challenges faced by developers for optimisation become apparent. There are huge frame rate drops in some areas, and blatantly poor draw distance in others, (with draw distance turned up to full.) In other areas like Tangelwood Marsh, where the graphics are stunning, draw distance is optimised and frame rate is better, but enemies tend to spawn out of thin air two feet away. This is especially amusing when its a 10 meter tall dinosaur. The game is still very good for the price and considering how hard it must be to make a versatile game for the mobile platform. I would by a third installment without question, knowing the potential future of this franchise. Where is 1.5 update, btw?

The bad news first: Kudos to another reviewer who mentioned that it took five installs of this game to get the Moga Power A working. I took their advice and finally got it working after a few installs, although after a couple of sessions it has stopped working and I'm unwilling to mess with it anymore. Secondly, e-mail support provides no feedback, no responses, and the Crescent Moon web site is similarly worthless. The good news is this game is pretty good. Controller support seems well done, and the tutorial messages reflect that you're using it instead of touch. The game play is somewhat simplistic (this isn't Skyrim regardless of what others may say) but it's fun. If the developer would fix Moga support then I would be willing to give it another try.

The touch controls in this game are so unwieldy that it's virtually impossible to play on a touchscreen device.  The sensitivity never feels right, regardless of how finely you've adjusted it.  The camera panning accelerates harshly.  The buttons are in odd places, demanding that you reach fingers into odd places on the screen. I went out and bought a bluetooth game controller for the explicit purpose of playing this game, but that did no good, because with the controller on & connected, the game just hangs at the menu screen (mountains & clouds), without any menu ever popping up. This might be a fantastic, immersive RPG like they advertise, but if you can't control the thing, you just can't play it.  $7 down the tubes until the devs deal with these gamebreaking issues.  I'm not holding my breath personally, as I've seen tons of requests for support on their also-broken website, with zero answers.    Uninstalled until they get around to fixing the controls.

If you purchase this game expecting to have access to dozens of armors, swords, bows, etc., you have forgotten that you are playing this game on your phone or tablet. The world isn't  large as in Morrowind or Oblivion, but should we really be expecting them to be? Let's remember that we paid upwards of $50 for those games, and just $7 for Ravensword: Shadowlands. With that in mind...  This game is amazing! The graphics are stunning, the combat is exciting, and the world is large enough to justify exploring in depth. There are several mounts, homes to purchase, and side-quests to conquer. Overall, this game has more than enough content to make us feel good about spending  seven bucks.  For the developers: Usually, when people give the developers "tips" to improve the game, they are either SUPER obvious ("I want more swords and armors! Whaaaa!"), or they are totally implausible ("Why cant we craft items? Or farm? Or specialize in herbology? Whaaaa!"). Some things to look into though: buying a home seems pretty pointless, you can't really be a magic based character, the benefits of some of the traits are so great they make the others seem useless. Thanks for a great game!

So I got this game with very high expectations and graphicly, they were met. The gameplay is fun, but the AI of the enemy is very underdeveloped. As the title implies the game does take some getting used to. For example, there are no waypoints to quests, so everything has to be found, which in a sense is kinda fun, but at the beginning it is a nuisance. Overall, I'd say   Pros: great graphics, fun combat, and a decent story.   Cons: confusing getting from quest to quest and horrible AI.

The story line is very short, rather lacking in depth and definitely isn't worth replaying unless it is expanded upon in later updates, which I doubt will happen. Bladed weapons aren't held properly and appear to come straight out of your characters fist when in first person mode. Not to mention the very small amount of NPCs to interact with. It is immersive though and keeps you wanting to play until the end. It just ends too soon.

It has only happened twice and each time it was after a long play session (over an hour). The tablet gets pretty hot while playing, so it seems to be pushing the limits. For me, this was definitely worth the money.

Like Aralon, this game has a beautiful presentation, nice audio, and simple controls. i dislike the "hero has to carry around food to eat" mechanism (which seems particularly silly when the "Eat: pork" notification (which lets me know that the PC just ate some pork) pops up during combat), but not enough that it will dissuade me from playing. Offers variable difficulty settings, something i always appreciate in games of this sort (and easy mode is REALLY easy). Offers some IAP options (e.g. gold), but they are not at all necessary - they're just there to give impatient (or exceptionally bad) players a leg up (in which case i'm all for it ;). Much shorter than Aralon - i played through Ravensword in a single weekend.

Very impressed! Best Skyrim like rpg out there. You can pick up and sell stuff on the tables, there are 3d models for stuff you can sell, overall very polished and fun.
Plays well, Good story, Great graphics, fun physics, Just straight up nasty. Great job devs! Was hesitant to pay but glad i did.

The tutorial worked, but I'm stuck endlessly (okay, ten minutes so far) on the loading screen afterwards.  I guess I could try on my GS3 as well, but judging by other comments that's bound to be a similar disaster. I'm hoping for a quick fix on both devices.  Update: I started another game and the game loaded correctly after the tutorial - and has been working fine so far (aside from occasionally mildly disappointing framerate). I've changed my rating to four stars, but that's merely based on the fact that it's now actually playable, as I won't have time tonight to spend more than around an hour playing it.
Absolutely amazing! Everything  about it is great. The graphics, the gameplay, the leveling system. This is a huge step forward for Android gaming.
I've only played for about an hour so far but the game looks & plays great. Absolutely the closest you can get to Elder Scrolls on a hand held device. I'm blown away!
Had an issue with the app & emailed dev. They were VERY responsive and fixed the problem. Thanks!
I played for 4hours straight :D no bugs. Definately the best RPG game on android
An hour in really enjoying this, some nice graphics superb voice acting and engaging dialogue so far...
Works great on both my N7 and N4. Loving it all so far
Good game so far works for me no crashes
Cool, Glad to see this on android. I really liked crescent moons games on iOS.
No crashes on my phone

Really good game, just like skyrim! It needs adjustable graphics settings tho. It lags in some areas and heats up my note. The graphics are excellent but i would prefer the option to reduce the effects as to conserve power, reduce heat and lag.
Really good, runs nicely, looks gorgeous, worth the price for sure.

It's a beautiful looking game other than the extra selectable hair which doesn't fit the games textures well and looks like everybody is wearing wigs (there's natural drawn on hair on some characters that looks great tho - sometimes you see it sticking out from under the wigged characters' wigs!)  I so wish I could select female characters too but these are minor things in what is an otherwise crazy beautiful and very fun, smooth running game - even at Nexus 10's monster resolution and with all the action happening.  It does too have IAPs tho (check inventory then store) but they're not needed or forced super difficulty to get you to buy them or anything.  So this still gets the full 5 stars I rarely give out.

A brilliant game and a fantastic example of just how far mobile gaming has come. Runs great on the Nexus 4. I wouldn't go so far as to say that it's like "Skyrim in your pocket", but it is as close to that as anything that's come before, and as such, really is a grand adventure with lots to see and explore, awesome graphics and a great soundtrack. I'd also like to thank CM Games for releasing a true premium game that isn't tarnished with IAPs (it has none). Top work. :-)

Everything so far is pretty impressive. Its best game play experience for me on my phone thus far! Graphics are top notch for lower res textures. The only thing I'm worried about is the size of the game really. It seems you are just on a tiny island with a bunch of dungeons scattered about. Really is a pocket sized elder scrolls.

I waited months for this game, so of anyone should be overly optimistic about it, it would be me. Sadly, this just isn't a good game. The graphics are horrid on my Nexus 7, along with the framerate, the controls are sloppy and difficult to use, and the game freezes too often. Happily, all of these issues can and should be fixed in a patch, and I will update my review when and if they are, but until then, avoid this game.
More games like this please , premium is way better than FREEmium.
I've only played for a few minutes, but it seems to be working well, love the graphics. I have high hopes!

This is what Android needs more of! AAA premium titles with a premium price, none of that freemium crap. This game is amazing, it's almost like a Elder Scrolls game for your phone or tablet. World seems huge and your character has free will. Graphics are amazing too. This game is highly recommended!

Fantastic game so far, I am very impressed. Thank you Crescent Moon. I only wish that in 3rd person the camera could move around your character. Update camera options and this is the best game to ever release on Google Play!
Can't wait to play!
